{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"60025efe-f200-4e5d-923a-8e7de7505083","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n**Why:** After an SDK update, your workloads need newer versions that match the new SDK band. `dotnet workload update` fetches the latest compatible versions of all installed workloads.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** only *reinstalls* workloads at their current versions — it fixes corrupted installs but won't pull the newer packages your updated SDK expects.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n| Scenario | Command |\n|----------|---------|\n| SDK updated, workloads stale | `dotnet workload update` |\n| Workload files corrupted/missing | `dotnet workload repair` |\n\nAfter updating, confirm with:\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"29e9a06f-00c8-4dfa-9e61-3b4bf52d2c06","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question about .NET CLI commands — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer:\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for your SDK band. This is what you want after an SDK update, as it pulls matching workload versions.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads without changing versions. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n\n- After a .NET SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the right choice because it ensures your workloads align with the new SDK version.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"5041:300A76:1B6846A:1E673E8:69FA8F72"},"id":"ccc7ed2e-0d42-4f5e-b853-aeb6a5bd92f5","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:46:51.425Z","parentId":"45c49ec0-1c9a-4aee-99dc-173f5c28b258"}
